<sect1 id="opt_stars_as_point">
<title>Stars As PointsOrbits (&starsaspoints;)</title>
<para>&celestia; can display stars either as points or fuzzy disks.  Which looks better is a matter of personal taste and the resolution of your monitor.  In general, disks make a clearer distinction between brightnesses of a star and look better at high resolutions (see Display Mode below).  Points tend to be of similar brightness, but may look better at lower resolutions.  Selecting Stars as Points may also make &celestia; run faster, but this is only noticeable when you adjust the visibility limit so that tens of thousands of faint stars are visible all at once.  The slider in the "Filter Stars" section allows you to look at just the stars that are closer than a specified distance.  Normally, it is set to one million light years, so that all stars are visible but you can drop it so that you are looking at only close stars to our own.  This may also improve performance on slower or older computers.</para>
