<para>On the <guimenu>Render menu</guimenu>, select <guimenuitem>Antialiasing and Pixel Shaders</guimenuitem>.  These are instructions to &celestia; to use certain graphical processing techniques when it draws images on the viewscreen.  &celestia; relies on some of these techniques for drawing certain objects properly.  In general, both choices should be selected.  &antialias; toggles Antialiasing (smoothing) of the lines used to render orbit paths and constellation figures.  &pixelshading; toggles Pixel Shading.</para>

<para>New in &celestia; &ver; are five possible <quote>render paths</quote> for Vertex Shading.  &renderpath; toggles among the five choices (the Render menu choice is grayed out).  Vertex Shading is a technique that draws (renders) graphical shades (haze, shadows, etc.) on &celestia; objects.  To see such shading, your must have a graphics accelerator card that renders shading via a process known as Open GL.  However, as mentioned earlier, not all graphics cards can handle vertex shading properly.  Sometimes, vertex shading must be set in advance to certain parameters.</para>

<para>&celestia; gives you five choices for Vertex Shading.  They are:  Basic, Multitexture, Nvidia Combiners, Open GL and Open GL/Nvidia Combiners.  The number of these available render paths you can cycle through with &renderpath; depends on the graphics card and driver version you have.  By default, &celestia; starts up with the highest quality rendering selected.  If you have a Nvidia Graphics card, select the last choice (Open GL/Nvidia Combiners); observe Earth and then cycle through the other choices.  You will see surface shadows and a haze appear on Earth.  If you have another brand of graphic accelerator card, cycle through the five choices while viewing Earth and choose the one that is most pleasing to you.  If you have no graphics card at all, the Basic or Multitexture settings are your best choices.  The Basic path will always work well, although rendering will be at a basic level only.</para>
